        // ── Units of Measure & Conversions (Article) ─────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Units of Measure & Conversions",
            Slug = "inventory-uom",
            Summary = "Manage the units a part can be counted, stocked, and bought in — and the conversion factors between them — from the Inventory Units of Measure tab.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 5,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 7,
            AppRoutes = """["/inventory/uom"]""",
            Tags = """["inventory","uom","units","conversions"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Units of Measure & Conversions\n\nA unit of measure (UOM) is how a part is counted — Each, Foot, Pound, Liter, and so on. The **Units of Measure** tab in Inventory (the rightmost tab) is where you define the catalog of units your shop uses and the conversion factors between them, so a part bought by the box can still be stocked and consumed by the each.\n\nThe tab has two sections, switched by the buttons at the top: **Units of Measure** and **Conversions**.\n\n### Units of Measure\n\nThe Units of Measure list shows every unit with its code, name, symbol, category, decimal places, and a checkmark on the base unit for its category. Click **New UOM** to add one, or click any row to edit it.\n\nThe UOM dialog has these fields:\n\n- **Code** (required, up to 10 characters) — the short identifier, e.g. `EA`, `FT`, `LB`, `KG`. This is what appears compactly in tables and on documents.\n- **Name** (required, up to 50 characters) — the full name, e.g. `Each`, `Foot`, `Pound`, `Kilogram`.\n- **Category** (required) — the dimension the unit measures: **Count, Length, Weight, Volume, Area, or Time**. Conversions only make sense within a single category — you can convert feet to inches (both Length), but not pounds to feet.\n- **Symbol** (optional) — the display symbol, e.g. `ft`, `lb`, `kg`.\n- **Decimal Places** (required, 0–6) — how many decimals this unit allows. Set `0` for things counted in whole units (Each), and a higher value for measured quantities (e.g. `3` for kilograms).\n- **Sort Order** (optional) — controls where the unit appears in pick lists.\n- **Base Unit for Category** (toggle) — marks this unit as the reference unit that other units in the same category convert against. For Length you might make Inch (or Millimeter) the base; for Weight, Gram or Pound. The base unit is the anchor all conversions in that category pivot through.\n\n### Conversions\n\nSwitch to the **Conversions** section to define how one unit relates to another. The list shows From, To, the conversion factor, and whether the conversion is reversible. Click **New Conversion** to add one.\n\nThe Conversion dialog:\n\n- **From UOM** (required) — the unit you're converting *from*.\n- **To UOM** (required) — the unit you're converting *to*.\n- **Conversion Factor** (required, greater than zero) — how many *To* units equal one *From* unit. For example, `1 FT = 12 IN`, so From = FT, To = IN, Factor = `12`. The dialog's placeholder reminds you of this shape (`12 (1 ft = 12 in)`).\n- **Reversible (auto-creates inverse)** (toggle, on by default) — when enabled, saving `1 FT = 12 IN` also makes the system understand `1 IN = 1/12 FT` automatically, so you don't have to enter the inverse by hand. Leave it on unless you have a one-directional relationship.\n\n### Why this matters\n\nUOMs and their conversions let a part flow through your operation in whatever unit fits each step: you might **buy** wire by the spool, **stock** it by the foot, and **issue** it to a job by the inch. As long as the units share a category and a conversion exists between them, Forge keeps the math consistent — purchase quantities, on-hand balances, and job consumption all reconcile to the same physical material. Define the units once on this tab, and the rest of the system (Parts, Purchasing, Inventory) can speak them.\n\n### Tips\n\n- Pick **one base unit per category** and define every other unit in that category as a conversion to it — that keeps the conversion graph simple and avoids contradictory chains.\n- Set **Decimal Places** to match how the unit is really used. Counting in fractional eaches usually signals the wrong unit; a measured material like sheet metal area may need 2–3 decimals.\n- Keep **Reversible** on for normal physical units. The only time to turn it off is a genuinely one-way relationship.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        // ── Advanced Reference (Reference) ───────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Inventory — Advanced Reference",
            Slug = "inventory-reference",
            Summary = "The deeper stockroom reference: single- vs. multi-location sites, lot and serial tracking with expiration warnings, bin statuses and the QC Hold/Release cycle, promising stock to a customer, and making sense of a long movement log.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Reference,
            EstimatedMinutes = 4,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 90,
            AppRoutes = """["/inventory"]""",
            Tags = """["inventory","reference","advanced"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Inventory — Advanced Reference\n\nThis is the deeper stockroom reference — the gotchas and judgment calls an experienced materials person hits, beyond the everyday flows in the Overview, Guided Tour, and Field Reference. Use it when a situation isn't obvious: a new site standing up locations, lot-tracked material, quality holds, or a long movement log you need to make sense of.\n\n## Single-Location vs. Multi-Location Sites\n\nYour shop runs in one of two modes, and your admin sets which one during setup. The everyday actions — Receive, Use, Count — feel the same either way. What changes is whether you have to say *where*.\n\n- **Single-location.** Your whole on-hand for a part is one pooled number. The stockroom is treated as one place, so the **Location** field is hidden — you just record that stock came in, went out, or was recounted, and it all lands in the default spot. This is right for a shop with one stockroom where finding a part is never the problem.\n- **Multi-location.** Stock is tracked separately per location or plant, so a **Location** menu appears when you receive, use, or count — you say exactly which bin the stock entered or left. This is what you want when you have more than one stockroom, a separate receiving dock, or multiple sites, and knowing which one holds the material actually matters.\n\nIn multi-location mode, moving material between two places is a real event, not a note — use **Transfer** on the Stock Ops tab so both bins update and the move is logged in your movement history. If you're not sure which mode your site is in, look at a Receive or Count panel: no Location field means single-location.\n\n## Lot and Serial Tracking, Expiration Warnings\n\nStandard parts are tracked by quantity alone — 500 of a part is 500 of a part. Some parts need more, and your admin turns that on per part:\n\n- **Lot tracking** follows material in batches, with an expiration date and first-expired-first-out picking so the oldest lot goes out first. Reach for it with food, pharma, chemicals, adhesives, or anything with a shelf life or a recall trail.\n- **Serial tracking** follows each unit by its own serial number, so you can trace a single item forward and backward. It fits high-value or regulated items where every piece must be accounted for individually.\n\nOn a lot-tracked part, the expanded bin detail on the Stock tab shows three things worth knowing:\n\n- **Lot Number** — your own internal lot or batch number.\n- **Supplier Lot Number** — the vendor's lot number, kept separate so you can trace back to their batch without losing yours.\n- **Lot Expiration Date** — when that lot goes out of date.\n\nExpiration is flagged for you so you don't have to read every date: a lot already past its date is highlighted as expired, and a lot within 30 days of expiring is highlighted as expiring soon. Lots with no date set aren't highlighted. Use the warnings to pull short-dated stock first and to catch anything that should be quarantined before it ships.\n\n## Bin Statuses and the QC Hold / Release Cycle\n\nEvery bit of stock in a bin sits in one of four states, and knowing them keeps you from picking something you shouldn't:\n\n- **Stored** — the normal state. Free to pick, transfer, or reserve.\n- **Reserved** — held for a specific job or order. Don't pick it for anything else until it's released.\n- **Ready to Ship** — staged for an outbound shipment, waiting to go out.\n- **QC Hold** — waiting on a quality check. Can't be picked or shipped until quality releases it.\n\nThe QC Hold cycle is the one to have down cold. Incoming material that needs inspection goes on **QC Hold**, usually right at receiving. While it's on hold it's locked out of picking and shipping, so it can't accidentally end up in a job or on a truck. Once it passes inspection, quality does a **QC Release**, which flips it back to Stored and logs the release in your movement history. If a part you expect to be available won't pick, check whether it's sitting on QC Hold.\n\n## Can I Promise This Quantity? (Available-to-Promise)\n\nSometimes the real question isn't \"how much is on the shelf\" but \"can I promise a customer this quantity, and by when.\" That answer weighs what's physically on hand against what's already committed to other orders and what's inbound on open purchase orders — so a part can show plenty on hand yet not be promisable because it's all spoken for. If your shop uses this planning view, it also projects a date when a requested quantity can first be covered, based on when open orders are due to arrive. It's a supply-and-demand picture, not a raw on-hand count, and your planners may lean on it when quoting delivery dates.\n\n## Making Sense of a Long Movement Log\n\nThe Movements tab is your full audit trail, and it gets long. Click a column heading to sort, and use the column filters to narrow it down. The most useful is the **Reason** filter — pull up only Receives, only Transfers, only Adjustments, and so on. Most reasons are recorded when you do the action, but two are written for you automatically: **Received** (when goods are received against a purchase order) and **Cycle Count** (when a count with a difference is approved). On the Cycle Counts tab you can filter by **Status** — Pending, Approved, or Rejected. Narrow to a single reason, status, date range, or person before you export, so you hand off a clean slice instead of the whole log.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        Log.Information("Seeded Inventory training modules");
    }
